b'U.S. STANDARD\nATMOSPHERE\nSUPPLEMENTS, 966\n1\n\nPrepared under sponsorship of\nENVIRONMENTAL\nSCIENCE SERVICES ADMINISTRATION\nNATIONAL\nAERONAUTICS\nAND SPACE ADMINISTRATION\nUNITED STATES AIR FORCE\n\nFor\n\nsale by the Superintendent\n\nof Documents,\n\nU.S.\n\nGovernment\n\nPrintirig\n\nOffice,\n\nWashington,\n\nD.C.\n\n20402\n\n- Price\n\n$4.00\n\nU.S. STANDARD\n\nATMOSPHERE\n\nSUPPLEMENTS, 1966\n\n_, ,.-_-_ ._,NK NoT\nr_\n,..._, _\n_ _\n\npB,ECEt;_G\n\n_LI_SD\'\n\nli-"l -- "....\n_;,.\'_z,\n\nAbstract\nThe U.S. Standard\nAtmosphere\nSupplements,\n1966 was prepared\nin response\nto a need for\natmospheric\ntables\ndepicting\nconditions\nother than the mid-latitude\nmean represented\nby the\ntables of the U.S. Standard\nAtmosphere,\n1962.\nTables of typical winter and summer\nconditions\nfor various latitudes\nare provided\nfor the troposphere,\nstratosphere,\nand mesosphere.\nThe models\nmerge into three sets of boundary\nconditions\nat 120 kilometers\nin the lower thermosphere.\nModels\nstarting\nfrom these boundary\nconditions\nthen branch\nupward\ninto atmospheric\nprofiles which are\nrelated\nto the wide range of conditions\nin the heterosphere\nassociated\nwith varying solar activity,\ngeomagnetic\nactivity,\nand zenith angle of the sun.\nThe substance\nof this publication\nis two major sets of tables:\nthose for the region below !20\nkilometers,\nkeyed to seasonal\nand latitudinal\nvariations;\nand those for 120 to 1,000 kilometers,\nkeyed to solar and geomagnetic\nactivity\nand solar angle.\nThese two sets of tables,\nthough separated, have mutual boundary\nconditions\nso that users will be able to select for any location,\nseason,\nand solar activity\nthe appropriate\ncontinuous\nprofiles\nfrom the surface\nup to 1,000 kilometers.\nProfiles\nof atmospheric\nproperties\nfor any orbital or re-entry\ntrajectory\ncan thus be estimated.\nIn addition,\nthis publication\ncontains\ninformation\non diurnal\nvariations\nin density\nup to 90 kilometers,\nrefined analytic expressions\nwhich can be used to represent\npressure\nand density profiles\nof the 1962 Standard\nand these Supplementary\nAtmospheres\nto 80 kilometers,\nand a mid-latitude\nozone model up to 50 kilometers.\nTables providing\nthe altitude\nvariation\nof equal geopotential\nsurfaces\nas a function\nof latitude\nare also included\nto facilitate\napplication\nof the atmospheric\ntables to all locations.\nFor those interested\nin aircraft pressure\naltimetry,\na set of detailed pressurealtitude tables for levels from the surface up to 10 millibars\nis included.\nThe general\nbackground\nleading\nto development\nof these tables is contained\nin the foreword.\nTechnical\nbackground\nis presented\nin Part 1-Basis\nof the Tables.\nParts 2 and 3 provide detailed\ninsight\non the development\nof the two major sets of tables and include\npresentations\nof pertinent\nsupporting\ndata.\nPart 4 contains\nthe additional\nmaterial\non analytic\napproximations,\nozone, and\nlatitude-altitude\nrelations\nand Parts 5 and 6 are the major tables of the atmosphere.\nThroughout\nthe document,\nfigures and tables have been introduced\nto permit visual comparisons\nof the varying\nconditions\npresented.\nMajor tables are presented\nin both English and metric systems\nbelow 120\nkilometers.\nAbove 120 kilometers\nonly metric tables are provided.\n\nPB,ECEDING\n\nPAGE\n\nBLANK.\n\nNOT\n\nFILMED.\n\n_D\n\nr\'r_r-l-._,..\n\n_\n\n\xe2\x80\xa2 Batten\n\nCollege\n\nObservatory\n\nInc.\n\nWhite Sands Missile Range, USA\nFor several\nyears COESA\nhas been attempting\nto assemble\ninformation\npermitting\nthe tabulation of vertical\nprofiles\nof atmospheric\nproperties\nas functions\nof latitude,\nseason,\nand other\nsystematic\ninfluences.\nSuch tables are required\nchiefly for scientific\ncalculations\nand investigations of the effect on aerospace\nvehicle design, of atmospheric\ndepartures\nfrom the accepted\nbase\nline, the U.S. Standard\nAtmosphere,\nspecific\nscientific\nexperiments\nand\n\n1962.\nThey will also prove useful in long term planning\naerospace\nvehicle\nflights in instances\nof great sensitivity\n\nof\nto\n\natmospheric\nconditions.\nFor locations\nand seasons\ncharacterized\nby a minimum\nin variability\nof\nthe type caused\nin the lower atmosphere\nby weather,\nsupplementary\ntables may be quite satisfactory as predictions\nof atmospheric\nconditions\nto be encountered\nfor a specific\noperation\nor experiment.\nIn other instances\na supplementary\natmosphere\nmay be the best prediction\navailable\neven\nthough it is suspected\nthat effects due to nonsystematic\nvariability\naround it are unacceptably\nlarge.\nHowever,\nreaders who intend to use these models operationally,\nas representations\nof variations\nin the real atmosphere,\nare advised\nto study carefully the material on limitations\n(Sections\n2.4 and\n3.6).\nThis may be particularly\nimportant\nfor precise\napplications\nduring and immediately\nsubsequent to geomagnetic\nstorms (both planetary\nand polar) in the 120- to 200-km region and at all altitudes within the auroral oval.\nAn example\nof such an application\nis precise\nephemeris\nprediction\nfor low-ahitude\nsatellites\nin nearly circular\npolar orbits.\nDevelopment\nof the new Supplementary\nAtmospheres\nhas been well coordinated\nwith that of\nCIRA\n1965 tCOSPAR\nInternational\nReference\nAtmosphere,\n1965).\nThis has been achieved\nthrough\nparticipation\nof some of the major contributors\nin both preparatory\nWorking\nGroups and\nby presentation\nof COESA\nmodels and studies\nat COSPAR\nmeetings.\nBoth sets of models give\nlatitudinal\nand seasonal\nvariations\nup to 80 kin.\nThough\nthese are somewhat\nsimilar there are\nxviii\n\nsome important\ndifferences,\nparticularly\nin the high latitude\nmodels,\nwhere the COESA\nprofiles\nappear\nto be in better agreement\nwith recent data.\nThe new Supplementary\nAtmospheres\ngive\nlatitudinal\nvariations\nin properties\nat all altitudes\n(up to 1,000 km) and seasonal\nvariations\nup to\nabout 250 km, so that continuous\natmospheric\nprofiles from the surface\ncan be obtained\nfor any\nlocation\nand time.\nNo seasonal\nor latitudinal\ninformation\nis provided\nin CIRA above 80 km.\nThis document\nis the result of the efforts of all Working\nGroup members\nlisted previously.\nThe cochairmen\nwould like to take this opportunity\nto thank each of them for his unselfish\ncontribution.\nHowever,\nfor an effort of this type a small, hard core group of dedicated\nindividuals\nis\nalso required\nto bring to fruition\nthe ideas of many people.\nSpecial\nrecognition\nwhich must be\ngiven\n\nto them is provided\nin the following paragraphs.\nIn addition to guiding the Working\nGroup through\nscvcral major meetings,\nDr. Luigi Jacchia,\nWorking\nGroup Chairman,\nis responsible\nfor extension\ninto the exosphere\nof what had originally\nstarted\nout to be a report on systematic\nvariations\nbelow 90 km.\nHe illustrated\nthe manner\nin\nwhich satellite-determined\ndensity\ndata can be classified\nby profiles\nwhich are logically\nrelated\nto solar activity\nand the time of day.\nHe followed this contribution\nby developing\na methodology\nfor obtaining\na family of exponential\ntemperature\ncurves\nwhich fitted these density\ndata after\napplication\nof the barometric\nequations.\nIt was adopted\nwith some modifications\nfor this report.\nFinally, Dr. Jacchia\nis responsible\nfor much of the text and tables describing\nthe atmosphere\nabove\n120 kin.\nThese tables also include\nhis findings on the geometry\nof upper-atmosphere\nas related\nto the earth\'s\ncoordinates\nand the relationship\nof solar (and geomagnetic)\nexospheric\ntemperature.\nAlong with Dr. Jacchia,\na great deal of credit must be given\nciate, Jack Slowey.\nHis competence\nin the programming\nand computing\nof tables of\nprofiles was invaluable\nin the tedious process\nof joining together\nthe families of lower\nhigher altitude atmospheres.\n\nparameters\nactivity\nand\nto his assoatmospheric\naltitude\nand\n\nDuring the several years of development\nof these tables, Dr. K. S. W. Champion was a source\nof strength\nand knowledge.\nAs a responsible\nTask Group Convener,\nhe refused\nto compromise\ntoward a less exact but more convenient\nsolution in joining the lower-altitude\nseasonally\nand latitudinally\ndependent\natmospheres\nto the high-altitude\natmospheres.\nWith the aid of his associate,\nFrank Marcos,\nhe performed\nextensive\nstudies of the available\ndata in order to present an interface family of curves above 90 km which gradually merge the seasonal\nand latitudinal\nvariations\nbelow this altitude to the upper-ahitude\natmospheres.\nThus the variability\nshown in the\n250-kin\naltitude interval is most likely to be fairly representative\n(excluding\nconditions\ngeomagnetic\nstorms)\nof the true but insufficiently\nexplored\nconditions\nin this region.\nDr.\npion contributed\nextensively\nto the development\nof text and tables for altitudes\nabove\nespecially\nthose between\n90 and 250 km.\nHe was\nmeetings\nwhen the situation\nseemed\nrather dark\naltitude\natmospheres.\nThrough\nthese discussions\nable to provide the guidance\nrequired\nto overcome\n\n100- to\nduring\nCham90 km,\n\nresponsible\nfor convening\nseveral Task Group\nduring\nattempts\nto join the lower- and higherand presentations\nof data, Dr. Champion\nwas\nthe grave difficulty encountered.\n\nAllen E. Cole and Arthur J. Kantor deserve\nmuch gratitude for their major responsibility\nin\ndevelopment\nof the supplementary\natmospheres\nup to 90 km and for their patience\nand continuing\nefforts during the several\nyears required\nto modify and attach the upper portion of their already\nwell used Air Force Interim Supplementary\nAtmospheres\nto the high-altitude\natmospheres.\nMr.\nCole led a Task Group of several Working Group members\nfor a number of years in these efforts\nand showed\ngreat skill in assimilating\nmany of their modifications\nin the original\npresentations,\nincluding those of Dr. Arnold Court, Frederick\nG. Minzner has been an invaluable contributor\nin all phases\nof the development\nof\nthis volume.\nHe was extremely\nhelpful in resolution\nof the problem involving the interface\naltitudes of the 0 to 90 km and the above 200-kin atmospheres.\nHe prepared\nmany task level working\npapers\non methodologies\nof joining the various families of atmospheres.\nHe also prepared\na subsidiary\naltitude\n\ntable applicable\nof geopotential\n\nto the family of high-ahitude\nsurfaces\nat all latitudes to that\n\natmospheres,\nwhich relates\nthe geometric\nat the standard\nlatitude, 45 \xc2\xb0 N.\n\nCOESA\'s\nU.S. Standard\nAtmosphere,\n1962 includes presentations\nof temperature\nas approximate analytic functions of altitude, up to 200 kin.\nAhhough very close fit of the temperature\ncurve\nwas obtained,\ndensity\nand pressure\ncomputed\nfrom this curve departed\nconsiderably\nfrom the\nStandard\nat certain altitudes.\nTherefore,\nit was decided\nthat additional supplementary\nmaterial\nxix\n\nshould be developed\nMiss Jean P. Mason)\n\nand included\nand Hermann\n\nin this volume.\nRichard\nA. Hord (with the aid of his associate,\nB. Wobus comprised\na Task Group assigned\nthis responsibility.\n\nThey were able to prepare\nindependent\nanalytic\napproximations\nfor density\nand pressure\nfor the\n1962 Standard\nup to 200 km and for the new Supplementary\nAtmospheres\nup to 80 km.\nThese\nshould\nprove invaluable\nto those concerned\nwith machine\nprogramming\nof interactions\nof the\nsensible\natmosphere\nwith aerospace\nvehicles\nin the mesosphere,\nstratosphere,\nand troposphere.\nFinally, the COESA Working\nGroup decided\nthere existed a requirement\nfor presenting\ninformation on a minor but extremely\nimportant\natmospheric\nconstituent,\nozone.\nWayne\nHering of\nthe Air Force Cambridge\nResearch\nLaboratories,\nthough\nnot previously\nassociated\nwith COESA\nefforts, was called upon and responded\nwith a valuable\nsection on ozone for this volume.\nThe technical\ncontributions\nto this volume\nof course\ncannot end with the preparation\nof the\ndraft material.\nThere\nmust be final overseers\nso that all material\nmay tie together\nlogically\nand accurately.\nResponsibility\nfor this fell to the three\nco-sponsoring\norganizations.\nAssigned\nas technical\neditors were Dr. K. COESA\nfirst started\nto update\nthe Standard\nAtmosphere\nin 1953, rough data were\npresented\nwhich\ndepicted\nthis variability\nup to 30\nkin, the middle\nstratosphere.\nThese\ndata were obtained\nfrom a limited\nnumber\nof radiosonde\nflights.\nHowever,\nthe requirement\nfor presenting\nvariability\nin a format\nsimilar\nto the tables\nin the Standard\nAtmosphere\nhad not been established.\nThe current\nCOESA\neffort to provide\nsupplementary atmospheres\nreceived\nits impetus\na little more\nthan five years\nago when expansion\nof the nation\'s\nspace\nprogram\ngenerated\nrequirements\nfor information on the variability\nof atmospheric\nstructure\nin\nthe design of second-generation\nscientific\nand military\naerospace\nvehicles.\nAt that time,\na decision\nwas\nmade to utilize\na comparatively\nlarge mass of data\ncoming\ninto the inventory\nfrom a new sensor,\nthe\nmeteorological\nrocketsonde.\nIt was\nthought\nthat\nsuch data, in conjunction\nwith the very much improved\n30-kin\nradiosonde\ndata,\nwould\npermit\nconstruction\nof typical\nJanuary\nand July atmospheric\nprofiles\nfor\n30 \xc2\xb0, 45 \xc2\xb0, 60 \xc2\xb0 , and 75 \xc2\xb0 N. latitudes\nand an annual\naverage\nfor 15 \xc2\xb0 N.\nThe extension\nof these\nnine\natmospheric\nprofiles to an altitude\nof 90 km was established as the goal.\nTo attain\nthis goal, data from a\nhandful\nof specialized\nrocket\nexperiments\nfor altitudes\nabove\nthose\nof meteorological\nrockets\nwere\nsubjected\nto extrapolation\ntechniques\nthrough\nwhich\nthe wind\nfield is related\nto gradients\nof pressure,\ntemperature,\nand density.\nIn July 1963, the COESA\nWorking\nGroup, meeting\nat Fort Collins, Colorado\nwas able to define a generally\nacceptable\nset of seasonally\nand latitudinally\ndetermined\natmospheres.\nSeven\nof these extended\nto 90\nkin.\nThe two 75 \xc2\xb0 latitude\natmospheres\nhad to be\nlimited\nto 30 km altitude\nbecause\nof a lack of data.\n\nHowever,\ndue to the different\nthermal\nregimes\nfound\nat high latitudes\nin winter, four additional\natmospheres\nwere defined\nto represent\nthe\nspheric-mesospheric\nconditions\n75 \xc2\xb0 (to 30 kin) in January.\n\nwarm and cold stratoat 60 \xc2\xb0 (to 90 kin) and\n\nAt this point,\nvery little\nadditional\neffort\nwould\nhave been\nrequired\nto provide\na follow-on\nCOESA\npublication\nto the U.S. Standard\nAtmosphere,\n1962\nwith detailed\ntabulations\nof these\n13 Supplementary\nAtmospheres.\nIn fact, the Air Force, in response\nto\nurgent\nrequirements,\npublished\npreliminary\ntables\nas Air\nForce\nInterim\nSupplemental\nAtmospheres.\nHowever,\nat the Fort Collins meeting,\nWorking\nGroup\nChairman\nJacchia\npresented\na summary\nof recent\nresearch\nindicating\nthat it had become\nfeasible\nto\nprepare\nmodels\nfor altitudes\nabove\n200 km which\nwould\nportray\nsystematic\nvariability\nresulting\nfrom\nchanges\nin solar flux and zenith\nangle.\nNew pressures from the aerospace\ncommunity,\nthis time from\natmosphere-space\ninterface\ninterests,\nmade it desirable to extend\nour supplementary\natmospheres\nto\norbital altitudes.\nUnfortunately,\nthere was little information\non systematic\nvariability\nfor altitudes\nfrom 90 km up to 200\nkin, above the maximum\naltitude\nof most rocket\nsensors and below the minimum\naltitude\nof most satellites.\nDespite\nthis\ndifficulty\nthe\nWorking\nGroup\ndecided\nto try to provide\na reasonable\ninterpolation\nacross\nthis region\nfor the seven\nbasic surface-to-90\nkm (15 \xc2\xb0 annual\nand 30 \xc2\xb0 , 45 \xc2\xb0 , and 60 \xc2\xb0 January\nand\nJuly) atmospheres.\nThe contemplated\ninterpolation\nexpressions\nfor describing\nthe\n\nrequired\natmospheric\n\nphysical\nprofiles\n\nobtained\nfrom satellite\ndrag.\nAlthough\nthe physical\nrelationship\nwas partially\nunderstood,\nit can still\nbe only roughly\nspecified.\nThe final goal of spanning\nthe 90- to 200-kin\n"ignorosphere"\nwas found difficult\nto attain\nin spite of intensive\nresearch\nby COESA\nstudents\n\nof the upper\n\nTo review\n\natmosphere.\n\nthe situation,\n\nthe COESA\n\nWorking\n\nGroup\n\nmet again in January\n1965 at the University\nof Miami.\nIt was agreed that an inadequate\ntheory is worse than\nnone when it must fit a great many accurate\nobservations.\nDensity\nprofiles\nacceptably\nclose\nto those\ndeduced\nfrom satellite\ndata can be computed\nfrom a\nfamily\nof empirically\nderived\nexponential\ntemperature\ncurves\nand\nthe\nbarometric\nequations.\nThus\ntemperature\nis continued\nas the defining\nparameter\n\n4\n\nU.S. STANDARD ATMOSPHERE SUPPLEMENTS, Miami was adjourned\nwith our goal\nand\nprocedure\nsupposedly\nwell\nestablished.\nThe\nlow-ahitude\nsupplementary\natmospheres\n(15 \xc2\xb0 N. annual and 30 \xc2\xb0, 45 \xc2\xb0, and 60 \xc2\xb0 N. January\nand July) terminated\nat 90 km with seven\nsets of temperature,\npressure,\nand density data.\nThough\nthe 90-km temperatures\nand pressures\ndiffered substantially,\ndensity\nprofiles\nof these atmospheres\nappear to be converging\nto a single\nvalue\nslightly\nabove 90 km.\nSince\nan\nacceptable\nfamily\nof high-ahitude\natmospheres\nhad\nbeen defined which now extended\ndownward\nto a single\nset of boundary\nconditions\nat about 120 km, connection\nwith the seven low-altitude\natmospheres\nwhich reached\n90 km appeared\nto be a simple chore.\nSome manipulation of the lapse rates between\n90 and 120 km would\nbe required\nsince consistency\nthrough\nthe barometric\nequation\nmust be achieved.\nAlso, consideration\nhad\nto be given\nto several\nnewly\navailable\nsoundings,\nsome of which\nhad been presented\nat Miami during\nTask\nGroup\nsessions.\nTherefore,\nit was decided\nto\npermit\nmodification\nof the seven low-altitude\nmodels\nto levels\nas low\ngreater flexibility.\n\nas 80\n\nkm,\n\nif necessary,\n\nto provide\n\nThe implication\nof this decision\nto join all models\nat 120 km is that latitudinal/seasonal\nvariability,\nso\nwell defined\nin the lower layers, becomes\nessentially\ndamped\nout and negligible\nabove 90 km.\nThis simplifying assumption\nwas not borne out by examination\nof most recent\ndata.\nMore realistic\nconditions\nfor\nwinter,\n\nat least\n\nfor middle\n\nlatitudes,\n\nare\n\nrepresented\n\nif the 30 \xc2\xb0, 45 \xc2\xb0, and 60 \xc2\xb0 N. January\ndensities\nat 120 km\nare approximately\n50 percent\nabove the Standard.\nMid-latitude\nsummer\nand low-latitude\ndata grouped\naround\na density\nsome 20 percent\nbelow standard\nat\n\n120 km.\nThe 15 \xc2\xb0 annual\nand 30 \xc2\xb0 , 45 \xc2\xb0 , and 60 \xc2\xb0 N.\nJuly atmospheres\ncould be conveniently\nextended\nto\nthat point.\nIn so doing, the density-altitude\nprofiles\nfor all\nranging\n\natmospheres\nhad to pass through\na density\nfrom 10 percent to 15 percent above standard\n\njust above 90 km, a level recently\nnoted to be isopycnic\n(near-constant\ndensity).\nThe concept of such a singular point has proved to be most useful.\nTwo new families of temperature\ncurves for the interface region above 120 km were developed\nto connect\nwith\nthe Jacchia\nhigh-altitude\natmospheres.\nOne\nfamily\nstarts\nwith\n120-km\nwinter\nconditions,\neach\nmember\njoining smoothly\nat an altitude\nin the 200to 250-km region with the corresponding\ncurve in the\nfamily of high-altitude\natmospheres,\nwhereas the other\nfamily\nstarts at 120-km summer\nconditions\nand in\nsimilar\nfashion\njoins\nhigh-altitude\natmospheres.\nThese\n\ncontinue\n\nupward\n\nto 1000 km.\n\nAnother\nimportant\npoint\narose.\nThe\navailable\nspring and fall soundings,\nalthough\nsparse,\nindicated\nthat density at 120 km is probably very close to standard.\nIn these soundings,\ndensities\nnear 90 km are\nalso shown\nto approach\nisopycnic\nconditions.\nIt is\napparent\nthat if we were developing\na new Standard\ntoday, density should be 10 to 15 percent greater than\nthe present Standard just above 90 km.\nSince density\nvariability approaches\na factor of 3 around 70 km and is\nknown\nto amount to orders of magnitude\nat several\nhundred kilometers,\nsuch a small discrepancy\nis not\nsufficient justification\nfor a revision of the 1962 Standard at this time.\nHowever,\nit does appear reasonable\nto provide additional\nrealism\nin a report on supplementary\natmospheres\nby\nincluding\n"spring/fall"\natmospheres.\nThe Standard\nappears\nto be a good\nrepresentation\nof spring/fall\nconditions\nup to about 70\nkm, above which a departure is convenient\nthrough the\n91-km isopycnic\nto 120 km, meeting exactly the basic\nfamily\nof high-altitude\natmospheres\nsuggested\nby\nWorking\nGroup Chairman\nJacchia.\nWith these considerations,\na density profile can now be constructed\nwhich depicts mid-latitude\nspring/fall\nconditions\nat low\naltitudes\nand\nsolar position\nactivity.\n\nconditions\nfor the heterosphere\nfor any\nand degree\nof solar and geomagnetic\n\nIn summary,\nthe goal of these efforts is a description\nof the complete\nrange of atmospheric\nproperties\ncommensurate\nwith known systematic\nvariations\nfor lower\naltitudes\ndue to latitude\nand season,\nand for the\nheterosphere\ndue to solar activity\nand angle.\nContinuity\nand internal\nconsistency\nare maintained\nbetween all latitudes\nand altitudes.\nTwo sets of tables,\none for the family of atmospheres\nbelow 120 km and\nthe other for 120 to 1000 km, are provided.\nThese\nfamilies\nare matched\nat 120 km.\nFurther\nrefinements\nare the\nSupplementary\nAtmospheres.\nA\n\nmean\n\nannual\n\natmosphere\n\nrather\n\nthan\n\nmonthly\n\natmospheres\nwas adopted\nfor 15 \xc2\xb0 N. since the monthly\nvariability\nof the makes\nit impractical\nat this time to develop monthly\natmospheres\nbetween\n30 and 80 km.\nRecent meteorological\nrocket\nnetwork\nobservations\nat Ascension,\n8 \xc2\xb0 S., Antigua,\n17 \xc2\xb0 indication\nof the magnitude\nof the latitudinal\n\n_gfl_Ol/Otl\n\nVOllCtlJlllty\n\n_iii_ii\n\n_II\n\nUF_C__A_)_t_U\n\nd.[\n\nLIIC_g\n\nin the atmosphere.\n\n2.2.1\nTEMPERATURE.\n-Temperature\nextremes\nat\naltitudes\nbelow 20 km occur in January and July at\nmost locations\nbetween\n30 \xc2\xb0 and 75 \xc2\xb0 N.\nIn the strato-\n\nsphere,\nhowever,\nsemiannual\nand biennial\ntemperature oscillations\ncomplicate\nthe annual temperature\ndistribution.\nThe magnitude\nof the annual cycle is\nlargest at high latitudes, decreasing\ntoward the equator.\nThe amplitudes\nof the biennial and semiannual\ncycles\nare largest\nnear the equator,\ndecreasing\ntoward the\npoles.\nThe phases, as well as the amplitudes\nof these\ntemperature\noscillations,\nchange\nwith latitude\nand\naltitude.\nA sufficient\nsample\nof observations\nis not\navailable above 30 km from which to establish\nthe vertical\n\nextent\n\nand\n\nmagnitude\n\nof the biennial\n\noscillation\n\nin equatorial regions.\nNorth of 15 \xc2\xb0 latitude, however,\nthe annual and semiannual\ncycles appear to be stronger\nand tend to obscure the biennial oscillation.\nObservations show that the semiannual\noscillation\ntwo pronounced\nmaxima and minima within\n\nproduces\nthe annual\n\nstratospheric\ntemperature\ncycle in tropical\nand subtropical regions\n(Cole et al., 1965).\nAt mid-latitudes\nthe combined\nsemiannual\nand annual\ncomponents\nshift the time of maximum\ntemperature\nin the stratosphere\ntoward early June or May (Batten,\n1963).\nRadiosonde\ndata which extend to 30 km indicate that\ntwo thermal regimes\nexist in the winter\nin arctic and subarctic\nregions\n(Figures\nIn January\nfour-to-one\n\nthe cold regime\nover northeastern\n\nstratosphere\n2.4 and 2.5).\n\npredominates\nby roughly\nCanada\n(McClain,\n1961;\n\nBelmont,\n1962), whereas\nthe warm regime prevails by\nnearly\neight-to-one\nin the Aleutian\narea.\nExplosive\n\n18\n\nU.S.\n\nSTANDARD\n\nATMOSPHERE\n\nSUPPLEMENTS,\n\n1966\n\nI\n\nI\n\n4O\n\n35\n\n75 \xc2\xb0 N. 2.9 as percentage\ndeparture\nfrom\nStandard.\nThe\nregion\nof minimum\nseasonal\nand\nlatitudinal\nvariability\nin density near 8 km represents\nthe first isopycnic\nlevel where\ndensity\nremains\nrelatively constant\nthroughout\nthe year regardless\nof location.\nA second\nisopycnic\nlevel appears\nto exist just\nabove 90 km where density profiles of all latitudes\nand\nseasons\ntend to converge\nor cross at a density roughly\n\nThe meridional\ntemperature\ngradient\n(Figure\n2.1)\nvaries with altitude\nand season.\nIn the troposphere,\nfrom the surface\nto roughly\n10 km, temperatures\ndecrease\ntoward\nthe pole in both seasons.\nThe northsouth gradient,\nhowever,\nis much larger during January\nthan July.\nIn July there is a reversal\nof the meridional\ntemperature\ngradients\nbetween\n10 and 15 km; temperatures\nabove these levels increase\ntoward the pole\nrather\nthan\nthe equator.\nThe thermal\nstructure\nin\nthis region is not as well defined\nin January\nbecause\nof the relatively\nlarge variations\nwith latitude\nin the\nthickness\nof isothermal\nand near-isothermal\nregions\nimmediately\n\nabove\n\nthe tropopause.\n\nIn the upper stratosphere\nand lower mesosphere,\n25\nto 60 km, temperatures\nincrease\ntoward\nthe pole in\nJuly and toward\nthe equator\nin January.\nThis is in\naccord with expected\nseasonal\nvariations\nin the solar\nheating\nat these\naltitudes.\nAt the stratopause,\nthe\nregion of maximum\ntemperature\nnear 50 km, the mean\nmonthly\ntemperature\nat 60 \xc2\xb0 N. is approximately\n17 \xc2\xb0 K\nwarmer\nin July than in January.\nThe corresponding\nchange at 30 \xc2\xb0 N. is 3 \xc2\xb0 K.\nThe meridional\ntemperature\nabove 65 km and temperatures\npole in January\nand decrease\n\ngradients\nreverse\nagain\nincrease\ntoward the\nin July in the upper\n\nmesosphere\nand lower thermosphere,\n70 to 110 km.\nTemperatures\nin this region are inversely\nrelated\nto\nthose in the stratosphere.\nA warm stratopause,\nfor\nexample,\nis normally associated\nwith a cold mesopause.\nGrenade\nsoundings\ntaken in northern\nSweden\nduring\n1963 and 1964 (Witt et al., 1965) confirm the existence\nof this inverse\nrelationship\nbetween\nstratopause\nand\nmesopause\ntemperatures\nduring\nthe summer\nmonths\nat northern\nlatitudes.\nNear\n80 km temperatures\naverage\n50 \xc2\xb0 K warmer\nin January\nthan July at 60 \xc2\xb0 N.\nSeasonal\ndifferences\nat this level, however,\ndecrease\nwith latitude\nto approximately\n10 \xc2\xb0 K at 30 \xc2\xb0 N.\nThe step function\nin the north-south\ntemperature\ngradient\nat 120 km (Figures\n2.2 and 2.3) is the result\nof an arbitrary\ndecision\nto establish\nthree sets of boundary conditions\nat this altitude,\nthe interface\nbetween\nseasonallyand\nlatitudinally-defined\natmospheres\nbelow 120 km and the family of atmospheres\nrelated to\nsolar activity\nabove\n120 km.\nThe altitude\ninterval\nbetween\n100 and 180 km is the least explored\nregion of\nthe atmosphere.\nOperational\nmeteorological\nrockets\n\n2.2.2\n\nDENSITY\n\nAND PRESSURE. -- Density\n\nfor thin\nof actual\nprofiles\n\n10 percent\ngreater\nthan Standard\n(Cole, 1961; Champion, 1965).\nThis concept\nof a second isopycnic\nlevel\nnear 90 km is supported\nby density observations\nand\nobserved\nwind and temperature\ndistributions\nbetween\n60 and 100 km.\nThe levels of maximum\nseasonal\nand\nlatitudinal\nvariability\nin atmospheric\ndensity\noccur\nbetween\n65 and 75 km and 100 to 120 percent\ngreater\nthan the cold regime density.\nAlthough\nthese\natmospheres\nconditions,\n\nare intended\nto depict\ntypical\nJanuary\nsimilar conditions\ncan occur in the arctic\n\nand subarctic\nduring other winter months.\nThe pressure\nprofiles in Figures\n2.10 and 2.11 are\nsimilar to those for density.\nA level of minimum\nseasonal\npressure\nvariability\nexists\nnear 85 km which\nreflects\nthe negative\ncorrelations\nbetween\ntemperatures at altitudes\nabove 70 km and below 60 km.\nThe\nlimitations\n\nthat\n\napply\n\nto the density\n\nbetween\n\n100 and\n\n120 km owing At\nhigher altitudes the spread of data continues.\nThe\nmeasurements\nrange-from several percent less to 65\npercent more than _tandard at 100 km and at 110 km\nfrom 20 percent less to 62 percent more than Standard.\nAt 110 km the July measurements\ndeviate from Standard by -- 15 and +5 percent.\nThe density deviations\nof three November and three February measurements\nlie between + 13 and + 62 percent, with a mean of about\n+36\npercent.\nTwo February\nmeasurements\nhave\nnegative deviations at 110 km. It is believed that\nthese do not represent typical winter conditions, but\ntropical conditions.\nSince 30 \xc2\xb0 latitude is relatively\nclose to 15\xc2\xb0 latitude, where there is no winter, there\nmust be a large gradient in temperature\nand density\nbetween these two latitudes, and thus large variations\nin the properties\nat 30 \xc2\xb0 latitude during the winter\nwould be expected.\nMean seasonal curves have been deduced from the\ndata in Figure 2.23 and plotted in Figure 2.24. 20\n\n2.23.--Departures\n\nI\n\n1965, 0310\n\nI\n\n40\n\nI\n60\n\n(percent)\nfrom\n\nStandard\n\nof 12 recent\n\nsame as kinetic temperature.\nAt higher altitudes,\nvalues of the mean molecular weight must be known\nto deduce the kinetic temperature.\nValues of kinetic\ntemperature\ncan be deduced directly in the region of\ndiffusive separation\nif the altitude profile of a single\nconstituent, such as N2 or 02, is measured.\nIndependent methods of measuring kinetic temperature directly\nare mainly optical in nature.\nThey include measurements of the Doppler broadening of resonance radiation\nfrom sodium or potassium and the deduction of temperature from the band emission of aluminum oxide\nby Armstrong (1963) and Blamont (1964).\nTemperatures\ncan also be measured on a synoptic\nbasis by measuring\nthe Doppler width of the atomic\noxygen airglow lines.\nThis is particularly convenient\nto do with the 5577 _ line. This line is primarily\nemitted in the vicinity of 95 kin, at or near the meso-\n\ndensity\n\nmeasurements\n\nat White\n\nSands\n\nand Eglin.\n\npause, a region of minimum temperature.\nArmstrong\n(1959) has obtained a considerable amount of temperature data from observations\non the 5577 _, line.\nThe\nresults of 15 early measurements\ngave temperatures\nin the range 180\xc2\xb0 to 220 \xc2\xb0 K, with a median value of\n190\xc2\xb0 K. More recent results have sometimes yielded\ntemperatures\nas low as 150\xc2\xb0 K and, on the other hand,\nsometimes as high as several hundred degrees.\nIn\nthe latter case, Armstrong believes that the observed\nradiation must be coming largely from higher altitudes,\nnear where the red line (6300 _) is emitted.\nRecent data include those of Hernandez and Turtle\n(1965). The temperattares\nmeasured\nat Bedford,\nMassachusetts\n(November,\n1964 to February,\n1965)\nlie between 150 and 260 \xc2\xb0 K, with a mean of 210 \xc2\xb0 K.\nThis compares favorably with a kinetic temperature\nof 208.5 \xc2\xb0 K at 95 km in the 45 \xc2\xb0 N. winter model.\nThe\n\n32\n\nU.S.\n\nSTANDARD\n\nATMOSPHERE\n\nSUPPLEMENTS,\n\n1966\n\n120\n\n30 \xc2\xb0 Summer\n\n30 \xc2\xb0 Winter\n\n110\n\n\\\n\n\\\n\n%\n\n10C\n\n9O\n\n_e\n\n_\n\n_m\n\nWinter\n\n(10 Flights)\n\nWinter\n\n(2 Flights\n\n----_,---- Summer\n\nonly)\n\n(2 Flights)\n\n8O\n\n7O\n\n6o\n\n-- 40\n\n-- 20\n\n0\nDeporture\n\nFIGURE 2.24.--Mean\n\nsummer\n\nand\n\nwinter\n\ndensity\n\ndata\n\nfor White\n\n20\n\n40\n\n60\n\n(percent)\nSands\n\nand Eglin\n\ndensity\n\ncurves.\n\ncompared\n\nwith\n\nidealized\n\n(Figure\n\n2.7) 30 \xc2\xb0 N. summer\n\nand\n\nwinter\n\nATMOSPHERIC\n\nI\n\nI\n\nI\n\nI\n\nMODELS\n\nI\n\ni\n\nI\n\nUP TO\n\nI\n\n120\n\nI\n\nKILOMETERS\n\nI\n\n!\n\n33\n\nI\n\n!\n\ni\n\n!\n\nI\n\n!\n\nI\n\n!\n\nI -\n\n120\nFort Churchill\n\xe2\x80\xa2...O, .....\n\n9 Dec\n\n1965, 1433 hrs (CST)\n\n--.---4--\n\n--\n\n11 Dec 1965,\n1\n\nDec 1965\n\n255\n\n60 \xc2\xb0 Winter\n\nMean\n\n2255\n\n]\n\n--\n\n/\nI\n\n/\n\n--\n\n//J\n\n--\n\n,o\n\n.-\n\n0\n\nI.\n\n\xe2\x80\xa2_:._i_"0._"\n\n,_; _\n--\n\n60 \xc2\xb0 Winter\n\nCold\n\n._\'_\'g""\'_\n_\n..Q.. (1966) have used multiple\nregression\ntechniques\nto determine\nthe functional\ndependence\nof atmospheric\ndensity.\nOne interesting\nfinding is that\nthe delay time for the density\nincrease\nfollowing\na\ngeomagnetic\ninstantaneous\n\nstorm\nvanes\nwith latitude,\nfrom\nat 70 \xc2\xb0 latitude\nto almost 22 hours\n\nnearfor a\n\nsatellite\nwith perigee\npoint near 20 \xc2\xb0 latitude.\nRoemer\n(1966), on the other hand, found no variation\nof the\ndelay\ntime\nwith latitudes\nup to 40 \xc2\xb0. Jacchia\nhas\nraised\nthe question\nwhether\nin DeVries\'\nstudy the\ndensity\nchanges\ncan be genuinely\nreferred\nto the\nperigee\nlocation\nsince the eccentricity\nof the orbits\nof the satellites\nstudied\nwas very small (0.013 to 0.027).\nSeveral\nexperimenters\nhave\nmade\nmass\nspectrometric\nmeasurements\nof neutral\ncomposition\nabove\n120 km.\nOne of these\nis Schaefer\n(1966) who has\nanalyzed\nthe results\nof four composition\nmeasurements\nmade with massenfihers.\nTwo of the flights were at\nChurchill\n(1400 CST, 18 February\n1965 and 0300 CST,\n19 February\n1965) and two were at Wallops\nIsland\n(0300 EST, 28 March 1963 and 1300 EST, 26 November\n1963).\nIt should\nbe noted\nthat\nonly the Churchill\nmeasurements\nmeasurement.\n\nconstitute\nThe data\n\na genuine\npresented\n\ndiurnal\nconsist\n\nvariation\nof ratios\n\nXIX\n\n(1963-66)\n\nof the ion currents\n\nand\n\nExplorer\n\nXXIV\n\nfor the different\n\n(1964-66)\n\nspecies\n\nas a function\n\nand not the\n\ndensity\nratios.\nHowever,\nthe variation\nof the two\nratios with latitude,\nseason,\nand time of day should be\nthe same.\nThe data clearly show that the 0/0,, ratio\nis larger\nduring\nthe daytime\nthan at night and also\nlarger at Wallops\nIsland than at Churchill,\nas can be\nseen in Figure 3.12.\nBoth observations\nare consistent\nwith larger\nvalues of 0/02\noccurring\nwhen the solar\nEUV flux which\ncauses\nthe dissociation\nis larger.\nObservations\nare also consistent\nmodels\nwhich show that the O/O.,\nthe summer\nthan in the winter.\n\nwith\nratio\n\nthe present\nis greater\nin\n\nHedin et al. (1964) and Hedin and Nier (1965) have\nmade a rather thorough\nanalysis\nof the results obtained\nfrom a flight of a magnetic\nmass spectrometer\nat White\nSands at 0730 MST on 6 June 1963.\nThey give number densities\nof N.,, 02, O, and Ar.\nThe temperature\nprofile,\nas determined\nby the slopes of the curves,\nis\nin satisfactory\nagreement\nwith the CIRA 1965 models.\nHowever,\nthe number\ndensities\nof the various species\nare lower than the model\nvalues.\nWhen\ncompared\nwith the corresponding\nCIRA\nmodel\nthe measured\n02 and O number\ndensities\nare lower by a factor of\n2.0, whereas\nthe N2 densities\nare lower by a factor of\n1.7.\nWhen compared\nwith the models in Part 6, the\ndensities\nare found to be\'much\ncloser at 120 km, but\nthe discrepancy\nis greater\nat 200 km, as can be seen\nin Figure\n3.13.\nAt 120 km the ratios are 1.5 for O.,\nand O and 1.1 for N2; at 200 km the ratios are 3.4 for\nO.,, 2.5 for O, and 2.1 for N2.\nSome of the discrepancy\nis probably\ndue to calibration\ninaccuracies.\nThere\nare three sources\nof this: (1) statistical\nerrors ranging\n\nU.S. STANDARD ATMOSPHERE SUPPLEMENTS, 1966\n\n52\nlO\n\njr"\n\nf\n/\n37050\'\n\n_\nf\n\n/\n/\n\n/\n\n7\n\n7z\n\no.9.\n1.0\no\n\nIt should\nbe noted\nthat whereas\nthe temperatures\ndeduced\nby Spencer\net al. (1965) tend to be low, those\nderived\nby Hedin et al. (1964) are higher than the supplementary\nmodels between\n170 and 200 km and about\nthe same as the models between\n130 and 170 km.\nBrandy (1964, 1965) has deduced\nrotational\ntemperatures\nfrom\nthe N._ 3914 _ band\nemission\nduring\n\n_7_58\xc2\xb044\'\n\n//\n\nLatitude\n\nComparison\n\nof\n\nauroras\nat Churchill.\nAlthough\nthere is a possibility\nthat the rotational\ntemperature\nmay differ from the\nkinetic temperature,\nat least the altitude to be assigned\nto the measurement\ncan be determined\nby means of\nthe technique\nof triangulation.\nDuring the study over\n800 measurements\nwere\nmade,\nwhich\nincluded\n75\n\nn(O)/n(O2)\n\nNighttime\n37050\n\n, NASA--14.08\nMarch\n\n58\xc2\xb044\n\nI\n\n0.1\n100\n\n120\n\nNASA--\n\nI\n\n140\nAltitude\n\n\'\n\nUA\n1963,\n\nFeb.\n\n14.95\n\nI\n\n1965,\n\n160\n\nI\n\n28\n\n0300\n\n0317\n\nEST\n\nUA\n\nI\n\n19\nCST\n\nI\n\n180\n\n200\n\n(kin)\n\nFIGURE3.12. - Latitude variation of n(O)/n(O2)\nmeasurements.\n\nfor nighttime\n\nfrom 5 percent\nat the highest altitude\nto 30 percent\nat\nthe lowest altitude for the N., profile and possibly higher\nfor the other density curves;\n(2) an error of up to 50\npercent\nin the laboratory\ncalibration;\n(3) an error due to\nlimitations\nof the theory used to relate the measurements made under dynamic\nconditions\nto the ambient\ndensity.\nSome interesting\ndensity and temperature\nmeasurements\nhave been made\nby Spencer\net al. (1965).\nResults\nare available\nfrom six thermosphere\nprobe\nflights\nin which\nthe N2 density\nwas measured\nas a\nfunction\nof altitude\nwith an omegatron\ngauge.\nTemperatures\nare deduced\nfrom the slopes of the N2 profiles.\nThe\nmeasurements\nwere\nmade\nat Wallops\nIsland\nat various\ntimes\nof day and year\nbetween\nNovember\n1962 and March\n1965.\nIn general,\nthe\ndensities\nare lower than the corresponding\nmodels by\nabout a factor of 2. The temperature\nprofiles from the\nfour earlier flights are shown in Figure 3.14.\nThey are\nin moderate\nagreement\nwith the CIRA 1965 (Harris\nand\nPriester,\n1964) model\ntemperatures.\nFor the\ntwo most recent\nflights the agreement\nof the temperature profile for the night measurement\nwith both the\nCIRA and U.S. Supplementary\nmodels is satisfactory,\nbut for the day measurement\nthe agreement\nis much\nbetter with the U.S. Supplementary\nmodel.\nSpencer\net al. (1965) conclude\nthat "the assumption,\nfor model\natmosphere\npurposes,\nof constant\nboundary\nconditions\nat 120 km should be expanded\nto reflect,\nprobably,\na\nsignificant\ndiurnal\nvariation."\nThe authors\nare in\ngeneral\nagreement\nwith this statement\nand had previously suggested\nthe same conclusion\nwith regard\nto\nlatitude\nand seasonal variations\n(Champion,\n1966).\nIt\nis believed\nthat there probably\nis also a diurnal\nvariation of properties\nat 120 km, but the present\ndata do\nnot provide\n\nconclusive\n\nevidence\n\nas to its nature.\n\nsimultaneous\naltitude\nand temperature\nmeasurements.\nData were obtained\nfrom auroras\nof intensity\nranging\nfrom I to slightly over III.\nThe observed\nrotational\ntemperatures\nare plotted\nin Figure 3.15.\nTaking into\naccount\nseasonal\nvariations\nand the effects\nof solar\nflux and magnetic\nindex,\none notes the approximate\nexpected\ntemperature\nranges from the tables in Parts\n5 and 6, given as a function\nof altitude\nin Table 3.8.\nTABLE\n\n3.8.--TEMPERATURE\n\nRANGE\n\nAltitude\nkm\n\n80\n100\n120\n140\n160\n\nAS\n\nA\n\nTemperature\n\nFUNCTION\n\nOF\n\nALTITUDE\n\nRange\n\xc2\xb0K\n\n171-224\n190-218\n334-380\n467-574\n550-671\n\nBetween\n80 and 120 km, agreement\nbetween\nthe experimental\ndata and the models\nis reasonable,\nalthough\nthe scatter of the experimental\ndata is large.\nProbably\nthe scatter\nis to be attributed\nprimarily\nto disturbed\natmospheric\nconditions\nthat exist during\naurora,\nbut\nmay also be partly attributed\nto differences\nbetween\nthe rotational\nand kinetic\ntemperatures.\nAbove 140\nkm the observed\ntemperatures\nare definitely\nlower\nthan those of the models.\nBourdeau\net al. (1964) have compared\nexospheric\ntemperatures\ndeduced\nfrom satellite\ndrag observations\nwith\nthe intensity\nof extreme\nultraviolet\nradiation\nmeasured\nby OSO-1.\nThe EUV flux observed\nduring\nthe interval\nMarch\nto May 1962 is shown in Figure\n3.16a.\nThe plotted\nvalues\nrepresent\nthe sum of the\nintensities\nof the twenty-two\nmost prominent\nlines in\nthe wavelength\nrange 170 to 370/_.\nOf course,\nthese\nlines represent\nonly a fraction\nof the UV up to 1750 A.\nwhich\ndeposits\nenergy\nin the atmosphere\nby its manifold\nvariations.\nEven if they were\nperfect,\nstatic\nmodels would represent\nonly idealized\nequilibrium\nconditions\nthat are never realized\nowing\nto the perpetual\npresence\nof rapid temperature\nfluctuations,\nsuch as the diurnal\nvariation\nand variation\nassociated\nwith\ngeomagnetic\nactivity.\nIf the temperature\nvariation\nnecessary\nto produce a given density\nchange\nat a given altitude is correct when the variation\nis caused\nby changes\nin solar activity\nin the ll-year\ncycle, then it cannot be correct when the same change\nin density\nis caused\nby the diurnal\nvariation.\nThis\ndoes not mean that we cannot\nreproduce,\nand even\nwith\ngood\napproximation,\nthe diurnal\nvariation\nin\ndensity;\nchange\n\nwe can, but to obtain\nthe observed\ndensity\nwe shall have to use a fictitious\ntemperature\n\nvariation\nthat\nThe equations\n\nof our\nallows\ncould\n\nknowledge\nconcerning\nthe lower\nsuch a leeway that all exospheric\nbe in error\nby as much\nas 25\n\npercent.\nOne of the consequences\nof the arbitrary\nisopycnic\nlayer\nat 120 km is the emergence\nin the models\nof\na quasi-isopycnic\nlayer,\nwhich\nat times of low solar\nactivity lies at 150 kin, but rises to 200 km at times of\n\n(I 0 -22 w/rn:_/c/sec)\n\n3.6\n\ntions at greater\naltitudes,\nan assumption\nforced on us\nby lack of information.\nBy systematically\nchanging\nthese\nboundary\nconditions\nwith T_, we could\nfind\ndifferent\nsets of temperature\nprofiles that would reproduce the observed\ndensities\nwith comparable\naccuracy.\nStein\nand Walker\n(1964) estimate\nthat\nthe\n\nmay be at some variance\nin Section\n3.2 that relate\n\nwith reality.\nT_ to local\n\nsolar time and to Kl, or a_, must be considered\nin this\nlight; the aim was to reproduce\nthe observed\ndensity\nvariations,\nand we cannot\nguarantee\nthat the corresponding temperature\nvariations\nare correct.\nIn addition,\nwe must consider\nthe fact that, owing\nto the many oversimplifications\none is obliged to intro-\n\nhigh solar activity.\nIn the region between\n120 km and\nthis second\nquasi-isopycnic\nlayer,\nthe variations\nin\ndensity\nwith temperature\nare inverted\nwith respect\nto those above it, that is, an increase\nin temperature\nengenders\na decrease\nin density.\nWe know that this\nis not so, at least for two types of variation.\nIn 1957\nand 1958, near sunspot\nmaximum,\nthe drag of Sputnik\nII (perigee\nheight 200 to 210 km) showed\nlively fluctuations\nin phase\nwith the decimetric\nsolar flux, although according\nto the models there should not have\nbeen any; and in 1963 and 1964 (sunspot\nminimum)\nmarked\nvariations\nwith geomagnetic\nactivity\nwere\nobserved,\nin phase\nwith those\nin the exosphere,\nat\nheights as low as 160 km.\nThe dimcuhies\ndue to the arbitrary\nisopycnic\nlevel\nat 120 km are partially\nrelieved\nby having three sets\nof boundary\nconditions\nat that altitude.\nThis makes\nit possible\nto\nproperties\nat\ntechnique\ncan\nof day, solar\nvariations\nare\n\nrepresent\ntypical\nseasonal\nvariations\nin\n120 km and higher altitudes.\nThe same\nbe used to represent\nchanges\nwith time\nflux, and magnetic\nindex when these\nknown.\n\nIt should also be kept in mind that the mechanisms\nthat cause the different\ntypes of atmospheric\nvariation\nmay involve\nenergy\ndissipation\nat different\naltitude\nlevels, and that this can be another\nsource of distortion\nof the temperature\nprofiles.\nIt must also be remembered\nthat the relation\nbetween exospheric\ntemperature\nand solar activity\nwas\nderived\nfrom only the descending\nhalf of one solar\ncycle, which happened\nto be the most spectacular\nof\nall cycles\nobserved\nsince 1749.\nIf the relation\nholds\nwithout change\nthroughout\na cycle and from one cycle\nto another,\nthe exceptional\nnature\nof the last cycle\nmay prove to have been a boon, inasmuch\nas it allowed\nthe models\nto cover\nthe largest\npossible\nrange\nof\ndensity\nvariation.\nNevertheless,\nwe possibility\nof a systematic\ntables\ncaused\nby our imperfect\ncoefficient\nof satellites.\nAtmosgenerally\ndetermined\nassuming\n2.2.\nIn a recent paper on satel-\n\nlite drag coefficients,\nCook (1966) concluded:\n"Between\nheights of 140 and 400 km at times of low solar activity,\nor heights\nof 140 to 600 km at times of high solar activity, the drag coefficient\nis almost independent\nof height,\nand at present\nfor most satellites,\nbecause\nof the lack\nof decisive\nevidence,\nthere is perhaps\nnot sufficient\nreason\nto abandon\nthe value of 2.2, which has been\nwidely\nused in above\n400\n\nkm\n\n234-468\n\n(low solar\nO\n\n- 67\n\n- 6\n\nactivity)\n\nor\n\n600\n\nkm\n\n(high\n\nfor passes\n\nfor local\n\nsolar\n\n500\n\n550\n\n600\n\n(kin)\n\ntime,\n\nover\n\nthe northern\n\ngeomagnetic\n\nor solar\n\nhemisphere\n\nmid-latitude\n\nminitrack\n\nstations.\n\nactivity.\n\nactivity)\nthe drag coefficient\nincreases\nwith height."\nAccording\nto Cook, the drag coefficient\nCl_ should\nincrease\nto an asymptotic\nvalue of 2.6 to 2.7, which\nis nearly\nreached\nat 800 km at times of low solar\nactivity.\nThe\nrelative\nuncertainty\nin Cm however,\nshould\nnot increase\nwith altitude;\nthe likely error is\nestimated\nat 15 percent,\nerror is about 30 percent.\n\nwhile\n\nthe maximum\n\npossible\n\nSince\na density\nvalue\ncomputed\nfrom\nsatellite\ndrag is inversely\nproportional\nto the assumed\nvalue of\nCm we must count on similar uncertainties\nfrom this\ncause\nin the model densities\nbelow 600 km at times\nof high solar activity,\nand below 400 km at times of\nlow solar activity.\nAbove these\nlevels there\nis the\nlikelihood\nof a systematic\nerror,\nincreasing\nwith\naltitude,\nthat\nwill make\nthe computed\ndensities\na\nlittle too high, on account\nof the assumed\nconstancy\nof Ct_.\nThere has been much discussion\nabout the\nancy\nbetween\nthe drag\nmethod,\nis too small to explain\nthe discrepancy.\nA word of caution\nabout\nhydrogen\nis necessary.\nAt times of high and even moderate\nsolar activity\nthe\ncontribution\nof hydrogen\nto the total density\nis negligible for altitudes\nup to 1000 km.\nThe situation\nis\nquite different\nat times of low solar activity.\nIn the\nmodel\ncorresponding\nto an exospheric\ntemperature\nof 700 \xc2\xb0 K, the number\ndensity of hydrogen\novertakes\nthat of helium\nat 900 km, whereas\nin the model for\n600 \xc2\xb0 K the crossover\npoint is down to 510 km.\nHydrogen is the only constituent\nfor which the densities\ngiven in the model rely entirely\non theory,\nand moreover it is the only constituent\nfor which\nthe total\nmass\nin the atmosphere\nshould\nvary greatly\nwith\nexospheric\ntemperature,\nbecause\nof the effect of the\nlatter on the escape rate.\nIn addition\nto the uncertainties\nthat obviously\nexist\nin the theory,\nwe must warn the had\n\nuncertainty\n_l_\n\n63\n\nconcerning\n\n_,t_t_tUlltt_l_U\n\ntZJ\n\nhydrogen\n\nttt_\n\nis one of many\n\n_A_lJll_lt_.\n\n\xe2\x80\xa2 tt_l_\n\nCtl_\n\ndisquieting\nsigns\nthat\nour models\nof atmospheric\nvariations,\nderived\nfrom satellites\nwith perigee\naltitudes\nmostly\nbelow 500 km, cannot\nbe trusted\nat\nmuch\ngreater\naltitudes.\nFor example,\nCook (1966)\nfinds from the drag of the\ndensities,\nemerges\nas the only significant\nfluctuation\nat that altitude.\nThe ion density\nin the F2 layer, as\nevidenced\nby observations\nof the critical\nfrequency\nfoF2, shows a large semiannual\noscillation\nin phase\nwith the density\nvariations\nof the neutral atmosphere\n(Radicella\nand Cosio de Ragone,\n1966).\nThis lends\nsupport\nto the view expressed\nby King and Kohl
